status: UNIMARC: Format of notated music: Type of score

definition (en): Score format consisting of a series of staves on which all the instrumental and/or vocal parts of a musical work are written, one under the other in vertical alignment, so that they can be read simultaneously
A musical score not primarily intended for performance use, with the notation and/or text reduced in size.

preferred label (en): vocal score, accompaniment reduced for keyboard
definition (en): Score where accompaniment is reduced for keyboard instrument(s), and the voice and/or instrumental solo part(s) remain unaltered.

preferred label (en): voice score, chorus score, accompaniment has been dropped
definition (en): Score where the accompaniment to vocal or choral parts has been omitted and only the voice parts remain.

Score format presenting only the principal musical parts on a minimum number of staves, and generally organized by instrumental sections. A conductor score is a performance part for a particular instrument of an ensemble work to which cues have been added for the other instruments to permit the performer of the part also to conduct the performance.
Score format giving all the parts on a minimum number of staves, normally two, as with hymnals.
Score consisting of a music notation where letters, numbers or graphic symbols indicate the finger position on the instrument or the name of the notes.
Score format giving the different vocal parts on two facing pages of the book.
Score of only voices and continuo, omitting the other instruments.
Score without vertical coincidence of voices.
Score consisting of a part containing only one solo for a voice of a choir

preferred label (en): score with only homogeneous groups of instruments of the orchestra
condensed score with text and chord symbols
definition (en): Score frequently used in modern pop music, consisting generally in a melodic line with letters and/or graphic symbols representing chords or finger positions on the guitar.
Score consisting of parts written with different orientation on facing pages, so as to enable reading by players standing around a table.
